#' Plot 2D embedding 
#'
#' Plot a 2D representation (embedding) of cells
#' @param embedding_mat Embedding
#' @param colour vector of variable to plot
#' @param randomize Logical. Whether to randomize data before plotting.
#'
#' @return ggplot2 object
#' @export
#'
plot_embedding <- function(embedding_mat,colour,randomize=T, size_point=2) {
  # create a data frame that will have the embedding as well as the colors
  embedding_obj <- data.frame(
    Dim1=embedding_mat[,1],
    Dim2=embedding_mat[,2],
    Var=colour )

  # randomize the order of the objects
  if( randomize ) {
    embedding_obj <- embedding_obj[ sample.int(nrow(embedding_obj)), ]
  }
  # create the plots
  if(is.numeric(colour)) # the color variable is numeric
  {
    #embedding_obj$Var <- embedding_obj$Var - mean(embedding_obj$Var)
    lim <- stats::quantile(abs(embedding_obj$Var),0.99)
    ggplot2::ggplot(
      embedding_obj, ggplot2::aes_string( x="Dim1", y="Dim2", colour="Var"))+
      ggplot2::geom_point(size=size_point)+
      ggplot2::theme_minimal()+
      ggplot2::scale_color_gradientn( limits=c(-lim,lim), colours=c("blue","light grey","red"), oob=scales::squish )
  } else {
    ggplot2::ggplot(
      embedding_obj, ggplot2::aes_string( x="Dim1", y="Dim2", colour="Var"))+
      ggplot2::geom_point(size=size_point)+
      ggplot2::theme_minimal()+
      ggplot2::guides(colour=ggplot2::guide_legend(override.aes=list(size=3)))

  }
}

Analysis of distortion matrices Q

First, let's concatenate the distortion matrices of different samples in the proper structure (one column per sample):

H <- unique(
  cbind(
    meta$donor_sample,
    as.character(meta$orig.ident),
    sub("[[:space:]]A$|[[:space:]]B$", "", meta$Sample),
    meta$Sample
    ) )

rownames(H) <- H[,1]

Q <- NULL
for( i in 1:model$aux$numSamples ) {
  Q <- cbind(Q,c(model$params$Qi[[i]]))
}
colnames(Q) <- model$aux$Samples
rownames(Q) <- paste0( rep(model$aux$geneIDs,model$aux$K), ".Q", rep(1:model$aux$K,each=model$aux$J) )

Remove the effect of technology

Let's collect and normalize all Qs

tab<- table( H[,3], H[,2])
tab
                   
                    pbmc1 pbmc2
  10x Chromium (v2)     2     1
  10x Chromium (v3)     1     0
  CEL-Seq2              1     1
  Drop-seq              1     1
  inDrops               1     1
  Seq-Well              1     1
  Smart-seq2            1     1
techs_check<- rownames(tab)[rowSums(tab)> 1] # Keep technologies that are present in both donors

lis_H<- list()
lis_Q<- list()

# normalize per technology
for( i in techs_check ){
    print(i)
    H_sample<- H[ H[,3]== i,]
    Q_sample<- Q[ , H[,3]==i ]
    Q_sample <- Q_sample - apply(Q_sample,1,mean) # remove mean
    lis_H[[i]]<- H_sample
    lis_Q[[i]]<- Q_sample
}

[1] "inDrops"

[1] "Smart-seq2"
H_all<- do.call(rbind, lis_H)
Q_all<- do.call(cbind, lis_Q)

### top genes 

# pca
top_genes <- order( apply(Q_all,1,sd), decreasing=T )[1:20]
svd_Q <- svd(Q_all[top_genes,])
Q_rot <- svd_Q$v %*% diag(svd_Q$d)
rownames(Q_rot) <- unlist(lapply(lis_Q, colnames))

# umap
set.seed(43)
umap_res<- umap(Q_rot, min_dist=0.01, metric="euclidean", n_neighbors=3)
rownames(umap_res)<- colnames(Q_all)
colnames(umap_res)<- paste0("umap", 1:2)

plot_embedding( umap_res, H_all[,2]) + labs(x="umap1", y="umap2", title="Normalize per tech")

# Generating svd

colnames(embedding_res_svd)<- paste0("embedding", 1:ncol(embedding_res_svd))

# Generating umap of 2 dimensions
